location.name: Aberdeen -- Township Road 373, E of Porter Lake

mediaNotes: Recorded using the vehicle as a blind.  In the first segment a lone male has just landed in a small roadside slough and is calling, with a breathy upslurred introduction to the call. Late in this segment the duck flies to an adjacent field and continues calling.  In the second segment the duck has flown to a small slough on the other side of the road, continues to call and can be heard foraging on the surface of the water, making quiet slapping noises.  At the end of this segment the duck takes off and returns to the slough on the other side of the road.  In the third segment the male has been joined by a female.  The male is no longer calling and the pair can be heard foraging at the surface and making the quiet slapping noise.  This is accompanied by very quiet calls that were not heard when the male was making the slapping sound on his own.

NOTES: GRUNT WHISTLES OF MALES CHASING FEMALES. FEEDING SOUNDS (MALLARD-LIKE QUACKING).[This is a relatively busy recording with a variety of calls given by this species and apparently several others.  As far as I can determine, there are "burp" calls by males, "quacks" by females, and Feeding Calls by both sexes given thoughout this recording.  There are also several "decrescendo " calls heard in the background (e.g. 2:03-2:05), but I cannot be certain that they were given by this species.  There appears to be a "cryptic" stop-start at 2:02.  Quality unchanged (2 - though probably more like 2-3 in many places) - CAM - 21 March 2005]. Other Behaviors: Court. Habitat: Pond.

NOTES: (Species Sound: frequent; Breeding Status: territorial paired?, breeding; General Climate: arid; Cover Density: sparse) Male Gadwall chasing female Gadwall, taking off from Benson Pond, circling, and landing again on Benson Pond.  This male, rather than heckling the female, seemed to be escorting her away from one or more other males that were approaching her on the pond.[This recording appears to combine the "Burp Call," which is best described by Cramp et al. (1977. Handbook of the birds of Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa: the birds of the Western Palearctic. Vol. 1. Oxford University Press, Oxford) and shown in Fig. I on page 491, with the "tickety-tickety-tickety" Feeding Chatter described in BNA.  Although several of the "burps" appear to lack the introductory whistle, the quality is different than that of the "quack" given by females.  Good series of the Feeding Chatter occur at 0:06 and 0:075.  Quality added (2, 2-3 - BEST between 0:05 and 0:085 before the song of Melospiza melodia) - CAM - 21 March 2005]. Other Behaviors: Mate, Perform Visual Display. Habitat: Wetland, Freshwater, Deciduous Forest, Riparian, Lake, Hedgerow.
